<DOC><DOCNO> AP890203-0053 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0632EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-03 0734</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0754</SECOND><HEAD>The Big Chill Continues</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   An arctic air mass maintained its icy grip on the northern andcentral sections of the nation today, generating dangerous windchills of 80 below, as freezing rain made roads treacherous fromTexas to Vermont.   Snow fell in Oregon, California, Nevada, Utah and Wyoming.   Temperatures fell below minus-20 degrees in Montana, Wyoming,North Dakota and Minnesota, making for a 100-degree differencebetween North Dakota and Texas.   At midnight, it was 36 degrees below zero in Cody, Wyo., and 34below in Broadus, Mont. The mercury plunged to a record low ofminus-14 in Goodland, Kan., where the old record of minus-7 was lasttied in 1981. It was the second consecutive record low for that city.   Winds combined with the cold to produce dangerous wind chillsacross the central and northern Plains. Wind chills between 60degrees below and 80 degrees below zero were common in Montana andthe Dakotas.   Freezing rain, freezing drizzle and sleet fell from north centralTexas to Vermont, with snow in extreme northern Ohio and northernVermont, making driving dangerous.   Showers and thunderstorms dumped heavy rain and small hail onsections of Texas and Arkansas, with some places getting more than 2inches of rain. A flash flood watch was in effect for southwestArkansas. Rainfall also was heavy in western Kentucky and southernIndiana.   In the West, snowstorms accompanied by wind buffeted Wyoming andColorado. Up to 8 inches of snow was predicted for Colorado mountainpasses. Snow also was heavy in a small section of Utah south of theSalt Lake area. Up to 8 inches of snow fell in the state.   More than 5 inches of snow fell Thursday in Salem, Ore., andheavy snow continued to fall over the state's western valleys today.   Winds up to 75 mph blasted through mountain ridges around LakeTahoe and California's Sierra Nevada. Up to 6 inches of snow fell in24 hours in the northern Sierra Nevada.   Today's forecast called for snow from Oregon to Idaho and thecentral Rockies, from Nebraska to the middle Mississippi Valley andover the Great Lakes and central New England; freezing rain andsleet from southeast Missouri to central Illinois and from westernand central New York to Connecticut; rain from the lower MississippiValley to the Ohio Valley and the Middle Atlantic States; scatteredrain showers along the California coast and dangerous wind chillsfrom the northern and central Rockies to the northern and centralPlains and the upper Mississippi Valley.   High temperatures were predicted from 25 degrees below zero tominus 10 from the northern Rockies and northern Plains to westernNebraska and northwest Kansas; from minus 10 to zero from northernIdaho to the Colorado Rockies, the central High Plains, the lowerMissouri Valley and the upper Mississippi Valley; the single digitsand teens from much of the Pacific Northwest to northwest Colorado,from the southern Plains to central Missouri and in northeastWisconsin and northern New England; the 20s and 30s from thenorthern Pacific Coast to Nevada, western and northern Texas, themiddle Mississippi Valley, the lower Great Lakes and central NewEngland; the 40s, 50s and 60s from the California coast to southernTexas, the lower Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys and the MiddleAtlantic States; and the 70s and 80s from the central Gulf Coast tothe southern Atlantic Coast and Florida.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 35degrees below zero at Cody, Wyo., to 74 degrees at Fort Lauderdaleand Key West Naval Air Station, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 61 cloudy; Boston 30 freezing drizzle; Buffalo 18freezing drizzle; Charleston, S.C. 60 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 33rain; Cleveland 26 snow; Detroit 24 cloudy; Miami 72 fair; New York36 rain; Philadelphia 41 foggy; Pittsburgh 32 drizzle; Portland,Maine 19 freezing drizzle; Washington 46 fog.   _Central: Bismarck -24 fair; Chicago 23 snow; Dallas-Fort Worth21 windy; Denver -15 fair; Des Moines -10 snow; Indianapolis 30freezing rain; Kansas City -4 snow; Minneapolis-St. Paul -21 fair;Nashville 48 cloudy; New Orleans 67 foggy; St. Louis 19 snow.   _West: Albuquerque 37 fair; Anchorage 4 fair; Las Vegas 50 windy;Los Angeles 51 cloudy; Phoenix 53 fair; Salt Lake City 23 snow; SanDiego 53 cloudy; San Francisco 45 rain; Seattle 11 windy.   _Canada: Montreal 7 freezing drizzle; Toronto 14 cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>